      "content": "The general consensus among economists is that the expansion of the social safety net has a negligible or even positive effect on labor participation, as it reduces poverty without significantly discouraging work. Studies consistently show that programs like the Earned Income Tax Credit and expanded unemployment benefits often encourage people to enter the workforce rather than discourage them. While some critics argue about \"welfare traps,\" the data overwhelmingly supports the view that a robust safety net stabilizes families and allows individuals to take calculated risks, ultimately boosting overall economic activity.",
